Assignment For C Language

Que1. What do you mean by Arrays? Give one example of array and how you can declare an array
             Answer - 1
An array is a collection of similar type of data items stored in continuous memory locations
It helps to store multiple values in a single variable instead of creating many separate variables

Declaration of Array

int marks[5];    // Declaration of array with 5 elements

Example Program

#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
int marks[5] = {80, 75,
90, 85, 70};
for(int i=0; i<5; i++) {
printf("Marks of student
%d = %d\n", i+1,
marks[i]);
 }
return 0;
}

                  Output

Marks of student 1 = 80
Marks of student 2 = 75
Marks of student 3 = 90
Marks of student 4 = 85
Marks of student 5 = 70

Que2. What do you mean by Functions? Write the types of functions and give one example in code of each type

                  Answer - 2
A function is a block of code that performs a specific task
It helps in reusing code and makes the program easier to understand and manage

Types of Functions

1. Library Functions (Predefined functions)

2. User Defined Functions

(a) Library Function Example

#include <stdio.h>
#include <math.h>
int main() {
    double result = sqrt(25);  // sqrt() is a library function
    printf("Square root of 25 is %.2f", result);
    return 0;
}

                   Output

Square root of 25 is 5.00

(b) User Defined
Function Example

#include <stdio.h>
void greet() {    // Function definition
    printf("Hello Students!\n");
}
int main() {
    greet();      // Function call
    return 0;
}

                     Output

Hello Students!

Que3. What do you mean by Pointers? Write a code how you can initialise the pointer

                   Answer - 3
A pointer is a variable that stores the memory address of another variable
Pointers are used for accessing data indirectly and for dynamic memory allocation

Example Program

#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
int a = 10;
int *ptr;       // Declaration of pointer
ptr = &a;       // Initialization with address of variable 'a'
   
printf("Value of a = %d\n", a);
printf("Address of a = %p\n", &a);
printf("Value of pointer ptr = %p\n", ptr);
printf("Value pointed by ptr = %d\n", *ptr);
    
    return 0;
}

                      Output

Value of a = 10
Address of a = 0x7ffeef...  (address may vary)
Value of pointer ptr = 0x7ffeef... (same address)
Value pointed by ptr = 10

Que4. What are the types of Arrays? Write in a code 1D & 2D included

                     Answer - 4
There are mainly two types of arrays in C

1. One Dimensional Array (1D)


2. Two Dimensional Array (2D)

Example of 1D Array

#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
int numbers[5] = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
for(int i=0; i<5; i++) {
printf("%d ", numbers[i]);
    }
return 0;
}

                       Output

1 2 3 4 5

Example of 2D Array

#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
int matrix[2][3] = {{1, 2, 3}, {4, 5, 6}};
for(int i=0; i<2; i++) {
for(int j=0; j<3; j++) {
printf("%d ", matrix[i][j]);
        }
printf("\n");
    }
return 0;
}

                       Output

1 2 3
4 5 6

Que5. Explain the types of Operators in code.

                Answer - 5
Operators are special symbols used to perform operations on variables and values
Different types of operators in C are

1. Arithmetic Operators

#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
int a = 10, b = 5;
printf("Addition: %d\n", a + b);
printf("Subtraction: %d\n", a - b);
printf("Multiplication: %d\n", a *b);
printf("Division: %d\n", a / b);
printf("Modulus: %d\n", a % b);
return 0;
}

                      Output

Addition: 15
Subtraction: 5
Multiplication: 50
Division: 2
Modulus: 0

2. Relational Operators

#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
int x = 10, y = 20;
printf("%d\n", x == y);  // Equal to
printf("%d\n", x != y);  // Not equal
printf("%d\n", x > y);   // Greater than
printf("%d\n", x < y);   // Less than
    return 0;
}

                      Output

0
1
0
1

3. Logical Operators

#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
int a = 5, b = 10;
printf("%d\n", (a < b) && (b > 0));  // AND
printf("%d\n", (a > b) || (b > 0));  // OR
printf("%d\n", !(a == b));           // NOT
return 0;
}

                     Output

1
1
1

4. Assignment Operator

#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
int a = 10;
    a += 5;   // a = a + 5
printf("Value of a = %d", a);
    return 0;
}

                     Output

Value of a = 15

5. Increment/Decrement Operator

#include <stdio.h>
int main() {
int i = 5;
    i++;   // Increment
printf("After Increment: %d\n", i);
    i--;   // Decrement
printf("After Decrement: %d\n", i);
return 0;
}

                        Output

After Increment: 6
After Decrement: 5
